This week, my new resolution came to me this week, and it feels possible, in part, because of what I learned by sticking with my dietary restrictions last year. In 2018, Im going to say no to stuff I dont want to do more often! 2017 taught me that I dont have to be...

And Ive been really happy with how removing most animal meats from diet has gone - I feel healthier, and Ive saved a ton of money on groceries. Plus, Im real proud for sticking w/a resolution - so much so that I didnt even plan on making a resolution for 2018. But, then...

... that I would have to constantly apologize and/or put other people out when they were making food or picking a restaurant when I was around,  BUT it wasnt a big deal at all. I never felt like I was an inconvenience or burden to the ppl I care about/who care about me...

My 2017 new years resolution was to commit fully to being a pescatarian, instead of the flexitarian diet I had been practicing for a number of years prior. Until last January, I felt like my choosing dietary restrictions would be a major inconvenience for my friends/family...

Sorry not sorry for my twitter thread this morning.
If youve ever felt similarly, my heart breaks with you. I will hold space for you. I believe you.

I know my experience, and even with people I really love & trust, Im scared to tell them because of the possibility of not being believed, of being asked to see if from his perspective, of being asked why I didnt say something sooner.
So, mostly, I just want to ask you to interrogate what keeps you from believing someone when they tell you about their trauma. Work on that.

Silence is not always complicity; silence is often survival. It can take time, like a really long fucking time, to feel safe enough to speak up; temporally, the likelihood of being believed/ getting justice is inversely related to finding space to use our voices.

Generally, I am not one to be silenced, but there have been moments in my life where being silent was the only thing I believed would save me. The #metoo campaign has done a lot to bring the spotlight on a critical issue in our lives, but Im skeptical of its long term efficacy.

I will carry this with me, as I carry being french kissed while asleep on a school bus in HS, as I carry an ex breaking in to my apt & waking me up with his yelling, as I carry a chipped tooth & a voice saying now no one will ever find you attractive, & more.

In sum: the way a man idk touched me last night made me feel apologetic for existing, & he felt justified in his actions because he believed he deserved to be able to see the stage (WHILE SEATED nonetheless). P quickl, I just want to move beyond it, but thats not a real option.

Believe ppl when they speak up against their abusers. Believe ppl even when the timing is inconvenient. Being assaulted/abused is dehumanizing. Feeling less than makes it hard to believe speaking up will do any good. Speaking up & not being believed only furthers the cycle.

At Thanksgiving, in a convo about Roy Moore with my dad (a man who loves me fiercely & without question would die to protect me), he honestly asked me if I believe the women. I couldnt have said yes louder or faster, but still my mom beat me to it.

In the moment, I couldnt muster the strength to defend myself. I had to walk away, leave the venue, ask a friend to drive me home. I felt like a shell of myself once again last night because of the trauma I have lived & get to relive for the rest of my life.

I have experienced a wide range of physical and verbal abuses across my time as a woman in this world, and while his hand on my hip/ass or the extent to which he pushed me was pretty minor in comparison to much of it, it triggered a lot of previous pain.

Which is to say, last night a man I dont know aggressively physically moved me out of his line of sight at a local show. When I said you didnt have to touch me, in a pretty polite tone, he responded with thats the only way ppl pay attention to me. WTF.
Im down for Dont put your hands on other people without their explicit consent 2018 and/or if you arent sure if its cool if you touch somebody, then dont FOREVER.
